Since \(t\) is in Quadrant I, \(\sin t\) is positive.  Using 
\[
\sin^2t + \cos^2t = 1
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
\sin t = \sqrt{1 - \cos^2t}
\]
we get
\[
\sin t = \sqrt{1 - \Bigl(\tfrac{2}{9}\Bigr)^2}
       = \sqrt{1 - \tfrac{4}{81}}
       = \sqrt{\tfrac{77}{81}}
       = \frac{\sqrt{77}}{9}\,. 
\]
